% ABSTRACT
%----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

\begin{abstract}
There is a long-standing debate on the relationship between economic growth and political development. This debate seems to agree in that there is a positive correlation between the two. Most of the explanations focus on institutional constrains (mainly via property rights) and the incentives of the business class to invest in technology and infrastructure. Though this paper recognizes this mechanism, it proposes an alternative (and not exclusive) channel. I argue that when the adoption of the income tax reflected an inter-elite conflict, it triggered other state-building institutions that promoted economic development. In turn, economic development altered landowners' hegemonic position inherited since the colonial period by introducing a new political elite invested in industry. Time-series and structural break analyses, plus a case study, support this hypothesis.
\end{abstract}



