\section{Introduction}

% Institutional Economics and Development
The literature on the relationship between political and economic development is vast. Without trying to survey all of it, there seems to be an agreement in that strong institutions cause better economic performance.\footnote{For the geography v. institutional design debate, see \citet{Sachs2003} for an example.} \citet[3]{North:1990vl} argues that ``institutions affect the performance of economies is hardly controversial,'' while \citet[185]{Przeworski2004} argues that this relationship is endogenous.\footnote{``[I]n the end, the motor of history is endogeneity [...] wealth, its distribution, and the institutions that allocate factors and distribute incomes are mutually interdependent and evolve together.''} Most of the explanations focus on institutional constrains,\footnote{\citet{Johnson2016}.} mainly property rights, and the incentives of the business class of investing in technology and infrastructure.\footnote{\citet[]{Leblang1996,Weingast1997,Iyer2005}.} When property rights are secured (via the state\footnote{\citet{DouglassNo}.} or via social norms,\footnote{\citet{Greif1994}.}) for example when a patent system allows inventors to perceive a private benefit, there will be incentives to invest in infrastructure, research and development.\footnote{However, see \citet[]{Clark:2009aa} and \citet[]{Mokyr:2016ty}.} This is usually the case when political and military elites are constrained by institutions, for example constitutions and/or parliaments.


% Hook and Contribution
This paper contributes to the literature by adding an alternative channel that explain political and economic development. Particularly, it complements our understanding of development from the sectoral conflict framework by introducing the \emph{dual sector economy model}. The political development literature has traditionally focused on socio-economic cleavages and potential alliances \emph{between} the ruling elite and politically excluded segments of the society. \citet[]{Moore:1966tn}, \citet{Tilly:1992rr}, \citet[]{Boix:2003db}, \citet{Stasavage:2008fr} and \citet[]{Acemoglu:1996rm} are among the most prominent examples within this tradition. In this paper I focus on political divisions \emph{among} the elite. The sectoral approach is hardly new. Just to mention some examples, \citet[]{Guillermo-ODonnell:1986ul} emphasized the positive impact of elite \emph{outsiders} on democratic transitions. \citet[]{Ansell:2014ty} and \citet[]{Boix:2015aa} argue about the role of economic inequality/equality among the elite on political development, and \citet{Mares2015} examine how income taxation in Europe is associated with inter-elite conflicts, particularly between the landed elite and the industrial elite. Though the relevance of different economic and social sectors has already been recognized, this paper complements this literature by bringing in the \emph{dual sector model} (a model of economic development). The dual economy model, as ``a model of structural transformation provides a useful theory of both why industrialization occurs [...] and why it proceeds slowly.''\footnote{\citet[p. 160]{Gollin2002}.} 

% Argument
My argument is that the emergence of an efficient and productive industrial sector altered not only the structure of the economy but the inter-sectoral balance of political power, making unsustainable the political monopoly run by the landed elite and inherited from the colonial period. The economic structural transformation, i.e. ``a secular decline of agriculture and substantial expansion of manufacturing,''\footnote{\citet[567]{Johnston1961}.} gave newcomers industrialists the necessary leverage that forced incumbent landowning political elites to make political and economic compromises. {\color{red}Somewhere else},\footnote{{\color{red}I don't know how else frame my argument without being repetitive. Hence I will cite myself. However, I am not sure this the right way to do it - most journals don't allow this?}} I have argued that the implementation of the income tax law in the 19th century Latin America was the keystone of these political conflicts and compromises, which triggered a series of other `state institutions.' In this paper, I expand on this idea by arguing that these `state institutions' caused long-term economic growth. In this sense, the paper provides an alternative explanation for why political and economic development happened together, emphasizing the impact the structural economic transformation had on promoting sectoral compromises that eventually lead to long-term economic growth. Next section introduces the \emph{dual sector model} and explains the mechanics of the structural transformation. Then, I explain my argument in detail. Later, I show evidence of different vector autoregression (VAR) and structural breaks models for a subset of Latin American countries, which I complement with an in-depth case study of Chile.


\section{Structural Transformations and the Dual/Balanced Sector Economy Model}

\epigraph{\emph{When by the improvement and cultivation of land [...] the labour of half the society becomes sufficient to provide food for the whole, the other half [...] can be employed [...] in satisfying the other wants and fancies of mankind}}{\citet[I.11.59]{Smith:1904aa}}


% Define/Introduce the Dual Sector Model.
19th-century German-American economist Friedrich List in his \emph{Nationale System der politischen Oeckonomie} was the first to make ``the case for balanced national growth.''\footnote{\citet[167]{Streeten1959}.} The dual sector (or \emph{balanced growth}) model argues that the economic system is divided into two sectors ``the advanced or modern sector, which we will call, somewhat inaccurately, the manufacturing sector,'' and the ``backward or traditional sector, which may be suggestively denoted agriculture.''\footnote{\citet[311]{Jorgenson1961}. Importantly, I follow \citet[87]{Kuznets:1967aa} in that ``mining is combined with [...] industry because of the large scale of its productive unit, its close connection with manufacturing, and the distinctive trend in its share in product and resources.''} The basic intuition of this paradigm is that in order for the industrial sector to develop, it needs first an efficient and strong agricultural sector. Contingent on efficient agricultural productivity, the emergence of the industrial sector goes from a low production sector eventually surpassing the agricultural sector. However, if the agricultural sector lacks economic efficiency, the industrial sector will hardly develop, leaving the country in an economic (and as I explain later, a \emph{political}) trap (too). 

% Shortcomings of the Dual Sector Model: Why Two Sectors, and the Third Sector
The intuition behind the dual sector model suggests that economic development involves a \emph{balanced} sectoral growth, i.e. \emph{both} sectors need to develop for the whole economy to develop. This idea counts with considerable support. \citet[151]{Lewis:1965nr} argues that ``[t]he secret of most development problems is to maintain a proper balance between sectors.'' Consequently, ``balanced growth is almost axiomatic as a desirable objective, for both developed and under-developed countries.''\footnote{\citet[169]{Streeten1959}.} The dual nature of the balanced growth model has been widely accepted too and forms part of ``a long tradition in development economics.''\footnote{\citet[8]{Kelley:1972zl}.} In fact, \citet[354]{Lindert1985} explain that the dual-sector model ``has become the dominant paradigm used by Third World observers.'' Though dualistic economies might sound as too much of an oversimplification, I follow \citet[325]{Dixit:1973aa} in that the dual economy model provides a significantly better description of the economy because ``it reflects several vital social and economic distinctions.'' \citet[280]{Johnston1966} also explain that ``[t]he reality found in most underdeveloped countries approximates this dichotomy between agriculture and non-agriculture sufficiently.'' \citet[326, ch. 15]{Dixit:1973aa} is right in that a ``major drawback of dualistic theories [...] is the total neglect of the service sector.''\footnote{He continues: ``As a very rough approximation, one might suppose these to expand in proportion to industry proper, and be absorbed in it for purpose of analysis.''} However the literature is consistent in that the third sector necessarily develops \emph{after} the industrial sector is developed. In other words, industrialization is just halfway down the path to development. For example, \citet[506-507, 513]{Galenson1963} argues that ``countries in which manufacturing output grew most rapidly also experienced the largest increases in tertiary employment.'' This is also true for the Latin American case. \citet[95-96]{Baer1966} explain that the textile industry in Latin America went through a process of automation freeing labor to other sectors.

% Mechanics of Development: Importance on the Development of the Agricultural Sector // Growth
Economic development depends on the emergence of the industrial sector which in turn depends on the development of a productive agricultural sector.\footnote{\citet[567]{Johnston1961} argue that this process ``seems to be a necessary condition for cumulative and self-sustaining growth.''} As \citet[59]{Kuznets1961a} puts it, ``economic growth is \emph{impossible} unless there is a substantial rise in product per worker in the agricultural sector.''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} This insight is shared by many other development economists. \citet[105]{Hayami1969} for example argue that ``[i]ndustrialization and modern economic growth are basically \emph{conditioned} by the level of agricultural productivity.''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} There are two main reasons for why agricultural development is a prerequisite of industrial development: efficient agricultures are more likely to supply the industrial sector cheap food and cheap labor. In \citet[498]{Johnston1951}'s words, ``[e]xpanded agricultural productivity releases people from the land for employment in industry [and] provides food for the growing population which is a characteristic of the industrialization process.'' This structural transformation is the key of economic growth. In fact \citet[2]{Landon-Lane2003} find that an important source of growth in developing economies is ``derived through the reallocation of resources [particularly] by drawing labour moving out of traditional sector employment into the modern sector where it is more productive.''

% First Reason why AGR is important for IND: efficiency.
The first reason for why a productive agricultural sector is key to industrial development is that more efficient agricultural techniques make agricultural production less labor intensive, allowing landowners to free workers which the industrial sector can rely on. The need for an improvement in agricultural production as a necessary step prior industrialization ``has been termed the `prerequisite' hypothesis.''\footnote{\citet[133]{Kelley:1972zl}.} Technologies such as ``crop rotation, pest control, seed breeding [and] fertilizer use [represent] the major potential source of agricultural labor productivity.''\footnote{\citet[62]{Ranis:1964uq}.} \citet[339-340]{Nicholls1961} shows that industrial countries had relatively more developed and productive agricultural sectors. In fact, \citet[57]{Gallo:1991kx} finds that in Bolivia, a primarily agricultural economy, ``[t]he tools employed in production were few and rudimentary, the use of fertilizers was minimal, and methods for conservation of the soil were practically unknown until the beginning of the 1950s [...] As a result, productivity was very low.'' However, highly industrialized countries such as Japan and Taiwan adopted \emph{prior industrialization} very efficient agricultural technologies such as higher-yielding varieties, fertilizers and other activities that improved farm practices.\footnote{\citet[571]{Johnston1961}. Similarly \citet[723]{Caselli2005} explains that poorer economies have inefficient agricultural sectors which at the same time are the mayor source of employment.}

% First Reason why AGR is important for IND: efficiency leads to surplus of labor.
Surplus of labor naturally leads to a reallocation of redundant workers into the industrial sector, which is the crux of economic development.\footnote{\citet[7]{Ranis:1964uq} argue that ``the development problem may be said to lie in the gradual shifting of the center of gravity of the economy from the agricultural to the industrial sector.'' In turn, \citet[51]{Leibenstein:1957aa} argues that ``a lack of of adequate non-agricultural employment opportunities lies at the very root of the economic development problem [...] For it is the lack of alternative employment opportunities that makes it impossible to shift any significant portion of the labor force to the non-agricultural sector.''} \citet[33{\color{red}?}]{Nurkse:1953aa} in fact argues that development \emph{means} ``to employ the `surplus labor' on the construction of capital.''\footnote{Similarly, \citet[621-622]{Matsuyama1991} points out that  ``[i]ndustrialization [\emph{consists of}] a shift of resources from agriculture to manufacturing.''} Moreover, the literature coincides in that the `natural role' of the agricultural sector is to provide labor to the industrial sector.\footnote{\citet[114]{Ranis:1964uq} argues that ``labor reallocation [...] is the \emph{inevitable} and \emph{natural} consequence of the continuous expansion of agricultural labor productivity.'' Emphases are mine.} For example, \citet[326, ch. 15]{Dixit:1973aa} argues that the ``agricultural sector \emph{must} fulfill [...] its dual role of supplier of labour to industry and of food for the industrial labour force.''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} Though \citet[]{Lewis1954} in his canonical work argued that there existed an `unlimited' supply of agricultural labor, a word of caution is in order. It was \citet{Robinson1936} who introduced the concept of `disguised unemployment.' Though it was first used in `structural' terms by \citet{Rosenstein-Rodan1943}, the concept was popularized by \citet{Lewis1954} who employed this term in `development' terms to signify \emph{redundant labor force}.\footnote{See \citet[203]{Ranis:1964uq} and \citet[289]{Jorgenson1967}.} Consequently the meaning of the supposedly \emph{unlimitedness} of labor should \emph{not} be taken literally. The concept rather means \emph{unemployment}. In fact, \citet[225]{Nurske:1961qr} points out that the concept ``is commonly used to denote all types of rural unemployment.'' In other words, there is `unlimited' supply of labor where the supply of labor exceeds the demand, or as \citet[102-103]{Leibenstein1957} puts it, ``where the existing labor supply could cultivate more land without loss of efficiency.''\footnote{In any case, \citet{Sen1966b} explains that a number of important predictions made by the dual sector model do not need this assumption to hold for the model to work.} One important consequence of this `unlimited' or abundant/unused labor is that the industrial sector attracts these workers \emph{without} increasing wages. \citet[99]{Ranis:1964uq}, \citet[280]{Skott1998} and \citet[730]{Fields2004} argue that a pool of \emph{redundant} agricultural workers (a `reserve army') is what prevents a rise in industrial wages.\footnote{Reallocating redundant workers implies that the industrial sector can actually \emph{absorb} agricultural labor surplus. Hence, it is argued that there must exist a sectoral technological bias, that is, the industrial sector should seek to employ labor-\emph{using} technologies \emph{and} the agricultural sector to employ labor-\emph{saving} technologies. See \citet[7]{Kelley:1972zl} and \citet[97]{Ranis:1964uq}.}

% % Second Reason why AGR is important for IND: cheap food
The second reason for why a productive agricultural sector is key to industrial development is because efficient techniques in agricultural production are able to supply cheaper foodstuff.\footnote{See \citet[312]{Jorgenson1961} and \citet[157]{Ranis:1964uq}.} Workers with access to cheap food helps industrial development by lowering the cost of subsistence, which is payed by the urban employer (urban wages). ``It is \emph{self-evident} that without increasing food output, the capitalist sector must remain in a stationary state.''\footnote{\citet[21]{Ohkawa1961}. Emphasis is mine.} Food surplus is a direct consequence of efficiency, and it just as important as labor the transference explained above. In fact \citet[60]{Kuznets1961a} explains that  ``\emph{if} output per worker in agriculture does not rise substantially, economic growth in the first case will be stopped by scarcity of agricultural products, and in the second case by scarcity of labour.''\footnote{Emphasis in original.}

% Results. Industrial growth needs to surpass agricultural growth. 
Finally, the long-run sectoral equilibrium between two \emph{efficient} sectors consists of an industrial sector with necessarily faster growth rates relative to the agricultural sector's. Following \citet[311]{Jorgenson1961}, \citet[59]{Ranis:1964uq}, \citet[291]{Jorgenson1967}, \citet[279-280]{Skott1998} and \citet[290]{Vollrath2009a}, the industrial sector is assumed to use capital and labor, consequently having increasing returns to scale, while the agriculture sector is assumed to use only land which is fixed, and labor which is the only input. This means that the industrial sector is \emph{structurally} protected: once the development process has started, \emph{ceteris paribus}, the agricultural sector must go behind with slower growth rates relative to the industrial sector. This structural transformation also keep affecting the labor structure. In fact, \citet[p. 134-135]{Harris1970} explains that while ``the creation of an additional job in the urban area reduces agricultural output through induced migration, additional employment can be generated in the agricultural sector without reducing manufacturing output.''\footnote{See also \citet[280]{Johnston1966}.} This implies that agriculture-industry productivity differentials ``may even increase with development.''\footnote{\citet[110]{Kelley:1972zl}.} \citet{Serrano2016} find that in Latin America there has been a declining role of agricultural exports as industrialization levels have increased. That said, it is important to say that ``once an agricultural surplus emerges that permits sustained nonagricultural growth, the agricultural sector declines relative to the overall economy but continues to expand absolutely.''\footnote{\citet[14]{Nerlove1994}.} In other words, it is the ``the proportional contribution of agriculture to the growth in countrywide product per worker''\footnote{\citet[45]{Kuznets1961a}.} what decays, hence the agricultural sector ``must also grow,''\footnote{\citet[534]{Ranis1961}.} specially given the continuing dependence on a constant supply of food.\footnote{\citet[2]{Nicholls1963}}

% social transformations
%Dixit in \citet[328]{Mirrlees1973a}: ``With these transformations come important social and economic changes. Increased urbanisation brings about increased commercialisation of economic activities, which is made possible by increased monetisation. This promotes development of capital markets, and allows easier intersectoral movements of savings. There is more transport activity. All these factors lead to an increase in the share of services in national product''.


\section{Argument}

\epigraph{\emph{Practically all governments are engaged in promoting one [group]. There are [...] landlord governments against the peasants and the industrialists}}{\citet[410]{Lewis:1965nr}}


The size of the industrial sector imposes tight constraints on the way politics is run by the incumbent landowning class.


Following \citet{Llavador2005}, I argue that an elite split along economic interests uses the state to influence certain policies and hence, growth and state building. A key element for my argument is that an elite divided on an economic cleavage is at the same time divided on their political preferences, particularly regarding their attitude towards state centralization


