\paragraph{Structural Breaks}In order to confirm my hypothesis, the theory should pass a number of tests. First, we should see that the income tax indeed altered the way in which one sector affects the growth rate of the other. Since the income tax was produced by a sectoral conflict, I expect that this is the case. In econometric terms, this is an analysis of a known structural break.\footnote{See \citet{Box1975} for a reference.} This strategy tests whether year $b$ when the income tax was implemented significantly changes the relationship between the two sectors. Essentially, a structural break divides the time-series into two subsamples by specifying a break $b$, before and after the income tax law.

Define the industrial sector as $M$ and the agricultural sector as $A$. Considering the following linear regression,

\begin{equation}\label{str:brk:1}
M_{t} = \alpha + A_{t}\beta + \epsilon_{t}
\end{equation}

\paragraph{}where $\alpha$ is a constant and $\epsilon_{t}$ a vector of innovations. A structural break, via a Chow test\footnote{\citet{Chow1960}.} tests whether the coefficients $\beta$ are different over the subsamples defined by break date $b$ (i.e. the year the income tax law was implemented). To do so, a Wald statistic is computed to test whether $\lambda = 0$. More formally, I test,


\begin{equation}\label{str:brk:2}
M_{t} = \left\{
\begin{array}{l@{,\quad}l}
\alpha + A_{t}\beta + \epsilon_{t} \; \text{if} \; t \le b \\
\alpha + A_{t}(\beta + \lambda) + \epsilon_{t} \; \text{if} \; t \ge b
\end{array}
\right.
\end{equation}

