% Introducing co-integration
The relationship between the two sectoral outputs in endogenous. If this endogeneity is not accounted for, the error term and the regressors will be correlated, and so OLS is inconsistent. Additionally, growth rates are usually integrated, that is, a time-series that ``wander'' up and down, yet they never revert to a given mean.\footnote{\citet[129]{Box-Steffensmeier:2014fe}.} \citet{Granger1981} introduced (and further developed in \citet{Engle1987}) the concept co-integration which means ``that if the components of $x_{t}$ were all I(1), then the equilibrium error would be I(0).'' In simple, a ``set of integrated time-series is said to be cointegrated if some linear combination of the series in levels produces a stationary series.''\footnote{\citet[193]{Durr1992}.} Consequently, I expect both industrial and agricultural growth to be \emph{individually} integrated, but also I expect them to be \emph{jointly} cointegrated. I test for cointegration in {\color{red}TABLE X}. Cointegrated vectors are widely common in the social sciences. \citet{Hatton1991} and \citet{Blunch2006} study sectoral growth, \citet{Ostrom1992} study presidential approval, \citet{Krause1997} tests whether voters have prospective or retrospective expectations, \citet{Fish2007} study the relationship between democratization and economic liberalization, \citet{Haber2011} study the relationship between natural resource ownership and authoritarianism, \citet{Sobel2011} study the relationship between persistence and institutional change, \citet[489]{Herzer2012} ``estimate the long-run effect of income inequality on per-capita income,'' and \citet{Blaydes2011} study caloric consumption and regime type. This paper adds to this literature by studying political and economic development with a focus on sectoral conflicts.

% Models for cointegrated vectors.
Cointegrated time-series need a special method to be estimated. If traditional methods are used, given the interdependent relationship of these kinds of time-series, the results can be affected by the `spurious regression' problem.\footnote{\citet[142-143]{Ostrom1992}.} Cointegration necessarily ``implies a particular kind of model,''\footnote{\citet[p. 571]{Wooldridge2002}.} which can be the Engle-Granger single-equation procedure\footnote{Or alternatively the two step regression error correction model (ECMs) - see \citet[264-265]{Fish2007}. For a comparison between the one and two-steep procedure, see \citet[84]{DeBoef2001} and \citet{Banerjee1993}.} or the Johansen's vector-autoregression method (VAR).\footnote{\citet[164]{Box-Steffensmeier:2014fe}.} \citet[244]{Beck1992} argues that with less than 100 observations ``the two-step procedure will not be optimal.'' Consequently, I will estimate the time-series using the vector-autoregression approach (VAR) specified in \citet[]{Johansen1988} which among several advantages, it is estimated via MLE. 

% VAR and Granger Tests and IRFs.
I am interested in whether the introduction of the income tax as a political institution is associated with a structural change in the economy. In other words, I test whether institutional development is correlated with a secular decline of agriculture and substantial expansion of manufacturing, that is, with modern economic growth (as predicted by the dual sector model). VAR models are well equipped for answering this question. Given that ``it is often difficult to draw any conclusion from the large number of coefficient estimates in a VAR system,''\footnote{\citet[159]{Lutkepohl2004}.} this methodology offers two additional (and complementary) strategies to analyze cointegrated variables. The first one is the Granger-causality test. \citet[42]{Lutkepohl2006} explains that if some variable $X$ forecasts variable $Y$ (and not the other way around), $X$ is said to `Granger-cause' $Y$.\footnote{\citet[197]{Durr1992} explains that ``a standard Granger causality test ought to demonstrate that both lagged changes in $X$ and lagged values of the error correction component cause current changes in $Y$.''} 






