\subsection{Engle-Granger Regressions and Error Correction Models}


\citet{Engle1987a} proposed a two-stage approach to estimate cointegrated variables. In the first stage, the analyst estimates a \emph{cointegrating regression}, represented in \autoref{egranger:step:1}. Once the model is fitted, the estimated residuals $\hat\epsilon_{it}$ are saved for the next stage, the \emph{error correction model} (\autoref{egranger:step:2:a} and \autoref{egranger:step:2:b}). In the first stage, I fit the next dynamic regression in levels via OLS,\footnote{``In levels'' means not differenced. Static OLS models can be specially biased in small samples due to serial auto-correlation. Hence I fitted a ``dynamic'' regression, i.e. I included the first lag of the \texttt{Industrial Output} variable. See example in \citet[162]{Box-Steffensmeier:2014fe}.}

\begin{equation}\label{egranger:step:1}
\text{Industrial Output}_{it} = \alpha_{1} + \alpha_{2}\text{Agricultural Output}_{it-1} + \alpha_{3}\text{Industrial Output}_{it-1} + \epsilon_{it}
\end{equation}

\paragraph{}for country $i$, and year $t$. Once \autoref{egranger:step:1} is estimated, I proceed to estimate the second stage, fitting both \autoref{egranger:step:2:a} and \autoref{egranger:step:2:b} via OLS.\footnote{Following \citet[162]{Box-Steffensmeier:2014fe}, ``each equation has identical right-hand side variables.''} Both equations are generic dynamic models. Depending on the country and the results of different tests for lag length,\footnote{See details in \citet[112]{Lutkepohl2004}.} more (or less) lags were considered.\footnote{However, it is always the case that the right-hand side of both equations has the same set of variables.} Note that for this stage I fit a parameter $\lambda$ for the quantity $\hat\epsilon_{it}$, from the previous stage.

\begin{equation}\label{egranger:step:2:a}
\bigtriangleup\text{Industrial Output}_{it} = \beta_{1} + \beta_{2}\bigtriangleup\text{Agricultural Output}_{it-1} + \beta_{3}\bigtriangleup\text{Industrial Output}_{it-1} + \lambda\hat\epsilon_{it-1} + u_{it}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}\label{egranger:step:2:b}
\bigtriangleup\text{Agricultural Output}_{it} = \beta_{1} + \beta_{2}\bigtriangleup\text{Industrial Output}_{it-1} + \beta_{3}\bigtriangleup\text{Agricultural Output}_{it-1} + \lambda\hat\epsilon_{it-1} + u_{it}
\end{equation}


Both \texttt{Industrial Output} and \texttt{Agricultural Output} are differenced one time.\footnote{Hence the symbol $\bigtriangleup$.} Substantively, $\beta_{2}$ denotes the short-run relationship between industrialization and agricultural development, while $\lambda$ represents the rate of convergence back toward equilibrium or the  ``\emph{speed of adjustment}.''\footnote{\citet[162]{Box-Steffensmeier:2014fe}. Emphasis in the original.} The two error correction models should have $\hat\lambda$'s with opposite signs. As \citet[163]{Box-Steffensmeier:2014fe} explain, ``if each variable responds to long-run equilibrium in the same direction, the system would remain in disequilibrium,'' indicating a lack of cointegration. A positive and significant $\hat\lambda$ in either \autoref{egranger:step:2:a} \emph{or} \autoref{egranger:step:2:b} would imply that as both sectors drift apart, the sector on the left-hand side of the equation grows faster to ``catch up'' with the opposite sector. For example, if $\hat\lambda$ in \autoref{egranger:step:2:a} is positive and significant, it would imply that the industrial sector adjusts to the agricultural sector's behavior, and as the agricultural sector grows and starts closing the gap between the two sectoral outputs, the industrial sector grows even faster to return to this equilibrium gap. Technically, in this example, it would mean that when \texttt{Agricultural Output} levels lie above the regression line, there is a tendency for \texttt{Industrial Output} levels to rise even higher in the next period.\footnote{I follow \citet[265]{Fish2007}'s setup here.} I interpret this dynamic equilibrium as the relative inter-dependence between the two sectors, where agricultural development Granger-causes industrial development.\footnote{This form of `causation' should not be confused with commonsense notions of causality. To say that $X$ Granger-causes $Y$ means that $X$ can be better predicted using the histories of \emph{both} $X$ and $Y$ than it can by using the history, i.e. lags, of $Y$ alone.} Once the agricultural sector grows, the industrial sector is able to grow even faster. In terms of sectoral conflict, this meant that as landowners developed and expanded, their own decaying accelerated as a result of this sectoral balanced growth. 





